{
  "Total body water is approximately what percentage of body weight?": "",
  "80%": "",
  "60%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "40%": "",
  "Total body water constitutes approximately 60% of body weight in an average adult, often referred to as the '60% rule,' though this percentage varies with age, sex, and body fat content.": "",
  "The intracellular fluid (ICF) compartment holds approximately what fraction of total body water?": "",
  "1/4 of TBW": "",
  "1/2 of TBW": "",
  "2/3 of TBW": "",
  "1/3 of TBW": "",
  "The ICF compartment contains approximately two-thirds (about 28 liters in a 70-kg adult) of total body water, making it the largest fluid compartment in the body, with the remaining one-third residing in the extracellular fluid.": "",
  "The major cation of the extracellular fluid (ECF) is:": "",
  "Mg2+": "",
  "Ca2+": "",
  "K+": "",
  "Na+": "",
  "Sodium (Na+) is the predominant cation in the extracellular fluid with a normal concentration of 135-145 mEq/L, and it is the primary determinant of ECF osmolality and volume.": "",
  "The major cation of the intracellular fluid (ICF) is:": "",
  "Cl-": "",
  "Potassium (K+) is the primary intracellular cation with an intracellular concentration of approximately 150 mEq/L, maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase pump, and it plays critical roles in maintaining resting membrane potential and cellular function.": "",
  "Hypernatremia most commonly results from:": "",
  "Water deficit (dehydration)": "",
  "Excess ADH secretion": "",
  "Excessive sodium intake in the diet": "",
  "Low aldosterone levels": "",
  "Hypernatremia (serum Na+ > 145 mEq/L) is most commonly caused by water loss rather than sodium gain, resulting in a relative concentration of sodium in the remaining body water, as seen in dehydration, diabetes insipidus, or inadequate water intake.": "",
  "Normal blood pH is maintained within the narrow range of:": "",
  "7.0-7.2": "",
  "6.8-7.0": "",
  "7.35-7.45": "",
  "7.5-7.7": "",
  "Normal arterial blood pH is tightly maintained between 7.35 and 7.45 by buffer systems, respiratory mechanisms, and renal regulation. Deviations outside this range can be life-threatening, with values below 6.8 or above 7.8 generally considered incompatible with life.": "",
  "Hypokalemia is dangerous primarily because it can cause:": "",
  "Only leg cramps": "",
  "High blood pressure only": "",
  "Cardiac arrhythmias and muscle weakness": "",
  "Only mild fatigue": "",
  "Hypokalemia (K+ < 3.5 mEq/L) is dangerous because potassium is critical for cardiac electrical conduction and muscle contraction. Low potassium can cause life-threatening cardiac arrhythmias including ventricular fibrillation, as well as generalized muscle weakness and paralytic ileus.": "",
  "The lungs regulate blood pH by:": "",
  "Adjusting CO2 exhalation rate": "",
  "Absorbing acid from the blood": "",
  "Retaining hydrogen ions": "",
  "Producing bicarbonate directly": "",
  "The lungs regulate pH through respiratory compensation by adjusting the rate and depth of breathing to control CO2 levels. Hyperventilation blows off CO2 to raise pH (compensating for acidosis), while hypoventilation retains CO2 to lower pH (compensating for alkalosis).": "",
  "The kidneys regulate blood pH by:": "",
  "Producing CO2 in the nephrons": "",
  "Excreting H+ and reabsorbing or generating HCO3-": "",
  "Only filtering waste products": "",
  "Adjusting respiratory rate": "",
  "The kidneys provide metabolic compensation for acid-base imbalances by excreting hydrogen ions (H+) and reabsorbing or generating bicarbonate (HCO3-). This process is slower than respiratory compensation (taking hours to days) but is more complete and effective.": "",
  "Calcium is important for all of the following functions EXCEPT:": "",
  "Blood clotting": "",
  "Maintaining blood osmolality": "",
  "Nerve signaling": "",
  "Muscle contraction": "",
  "Calcium plays essential roles in muscle contraction (triggering cross-bridge cycling), nerve signaling (neurotransmitter release), blood clotting (coagulation cascade), and bone structure. However, sodium, not calcium, is the primary determinant of blood osmolality.": "",
  "What is hypernatremia?": "",
  "Abnormally high potassium levels in the blood": "",
  "Abnormally low sodium levels in the blood below 135 mEq/L": "",
  "Abnormally low calcium levels in the blood": "",
  "Abnormally high sodium levels in the blood above 145 mEq/L": "",
  "Hypernatremia is defined as a serum sodium concentration above 145 mEq/L, most commonly caused by water deficit (dehydration) rather than sodium excess. It leads to cellular dehydration as water shifts out of cells into the hypertonic ECF.": "",
  "What is hyponatremia?": "",
  "A deficiency of sodium in the blood below 135 mEq/L": "",
  "A deficiency of potassium in the blood": "",
  "An excess of sodium in the blood above 145 mEq/L": "",
  "An excess of calcium in the blood": "",
  "Hyponatremia is a serum sodium concentration below 135 mEq/L, which can result from excess water intake, SIADH (syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion), or sodium loss. Severe cases can cause cerebral edema, confusion, seizures, and coma.": "",
  "What is hyperkalemia?": "",
  "A potassium level above 5.0 mEq/L that can cause fatal cardiac arrhythmias": "",
  "A sodium level above 145 mEq/L": "",
  "A potassium level below 3.5 mEq/L": "",
  "A calcium level above 10.5 mg/dL": "",
  "Hyperkalemia is an elevated serum potassium above 5.0 mEq/L, and it is a medical emergency when K+ exceeds 6.0 mEq/L because it can cause tall peaked T waves on ECG, widened QRS complexes, and potentially fatal cardiac arrest.": "",
  "What is metabolic acidosis?": "",
  "A condition where CO2 levels drop too low in the blood": "",
  "A condition where blood pH drops below 7.35 due to acid accumulation or bicarbonate loss": "",
  "A condition caused exclusively by hyperventilation": "",
  "A condition where blood pH rises above 7.45 due to excess bicarbonate": "",
  "Metabolic acidosis is a condition in which blood pH falls below 7.35 due to an accumulation of metabolic acids (as in diabetic ketoacidosis or lactic acidosis) or a loss of bicarbonate (as in severe diarrhea or renal failure).": "",
  "What does the term respiratory acidosis mean?": "",
  "An increase in blood pH caused by vomiting": "",
  "A drop in blood pH caused by hyperventilation and excess CO2 loss": "",
  "A drop in blood pH caused by hypoventilation and CO2 retention": "",
  "An increase in blood pH caused by excess bicarbonate intake": "",
  "Respiratory acidosis occurs when inadequate ventilation (hypoventilation) leads to CO2 retention in the blood. The retained CO2 combines with water to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), which dissociates to release H+ ions, lowering blood pH below 7.35.": "",
  "What is metabolic alkalosis?": "",
  "A drop in blood pH below 7.35 caused by excess acid production": "",
  "A condition caused by excess CO2 retention": "",
  "A rise in blood pH above 7.45 caused by acid loss or excess bicarbonate": "",
  "A respiratory condition caused by hyperventilation": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis is a condition in which blood pH rises above 7.45 due to loss of hydrogen ions (as in prolonged vomiting of gastric acid) or gain of bicarbonate (as in excessive antacid use), resulting in an alkaline shift in blood chemistry.": "",
  "What is edema?": "",
  "Excessive loss of fluid from the body through urination": "",
  "The abnormal accumulation of fluid in the interstitial tissues, causing swelling": "",
  "A buildup of red blood cells in the tissues": "",
  "Dehydration of cells due to high sodium levels": "",
  "Edema is the abnormal accumulation of fluid in the interstitial spaces of tissues, causing visible swelling. It can result from decreased plasma oncotic pressure (low albumin), increased capillary hydrostatic pressure (heart failure), lymphatic obstruction, or increased capillary permeability.": "",
  "What does the term hypocalcemia mean?": "",
  "Abnormally low calcium levels in the blood below 8.5 mg/dL": "",
  "Calcium deposits forming in the joints": "",
  "Elevated calcium levels in the blood above 10.5 mg/dL": "",
  "Excessive calcium excretion by the kidneys": "",
  "Hypocalcemia is defined as a serum calcium level below 8.5 mg/dL, which can cause increased neuromuscular excitability leading to tetany (muscle spasms), numbness, and characteristic signs like Trousseau's sign (carpal spasm) and Chvostek's sign (facial twitching).": "",
  "What is the bicarbonate buffer system?": "",
  "A system that only functions inside cells to buffer intracellular pH": "",
  "The most important extracellular buffer system using the equilibrium H2CO3 and HCO3- to resist pH changes": "",
  "A system exclusive to the lungs for gas exchange": "",
  "A hormone system that regulates kidney function": "",
  "The bicarbonate buffer system (CO2 + H2O <-> H2CO3 <-> H+ + HCO3-) is the most important buffer in the extracellular fluid, providing immediate resistance to pH changes by shifting the equilibrium to absorb or release hydrogen ions as needed.": "",
  "What does the term isotonic mean in the context of IV fluids?": "",
  "A solution containing only glucose and no electrolytes": "",
  "A solution with a higher osmolality than blood plasma, causing cells to shrink": "",
  "A solution with a lower osmolality than blood plasma, causing cells to swell": "",
  "A solution with the same osmolality as blood plasma, causing no net water movement across cell membranes": "",
  "An isotonic solution (such as 0.9% normal saline or lactated Ringer's) has the same osmolality as blood plasma (~275-295 mOsm/L), so it does not cause net water movement into or out of cells, making it safe for fluid resuscitation without disrupting cellular integrity.": "",
  "A marathon runner collapses after a race and is found to have a serum sodium of 118 mEq/L. She reports drinking large amounts of plain water during the event. What condition has developed, and what is the underlying mechanism?": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis from hyperventilation during exercise": "",
  "Hypernatremia from excessive sodium loss through sweat": "",
  "Dilutional hyponatremia from excessive water intake that diluted the serum sodium": "",
  "Hyperkalemia from muscle breakdown during the race": "",
  "This runner developed exercise-associated hyponatremia (dilutional hyponatremia) from drinking excessive amounts of hypotonic fluid (plain water) during the race, which diluted the serum sodium to dangerously low levels. This condition can cause cerebral edema, seizures, and death if untreated.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease presents to the ER with serum potassium of 6.8 mEq/L. The ECG shows tall, peaked T waves. Why is this considered a medical emergency?": "",
  "High potassium causes severe headaches and visual disturbances": "",
  "High potassium causes uncontrolled blood pressure elevation": "",
  "High potassium destroys red blood cells, causing acute anemia": "",
  "Severe hyperkalemia alters cardiac electrical conduction and can rapidly progress to fatal ventricular fibrillation or cardiac arrest": "",
  "Severe hyperkalemia (K+ > 6.0 mEq/L) is a medical emergency because elevated extracellular potassium depolarizes cardiac cell membranes, disrupting the normal electrical conduction of the heart. This produces characteristic ECG changes (peaked T waves, widened QRS) and can rapidly progress to ventricular fibrillation and cardiac arrest.": "",
  "A patient with diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) presents with rapid, deep breathing known as Kussmaul respiration. Their blood gas shows pH 7.15, low HCO3-, and low pCO2. What type of acid-base disorder does this represent, and what is the body's compensatory mechanism?": "",
  "Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation via hyperventilation to blow off CO2": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation via hypoventilation": "",
  "Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation via acid retention": "",
  "Respiratory acidosis with renal compensation retaining bicarbonate": "",
  "DKA causes metabolic acidosis due to accumulation of ketoacids, lowering blood pH and consuming bicarbonate. The body compensates through respiratory mechanisms (Kussmaul breathing), hyperventilating to blow off CO2 and raise pH, which is why pCO2 is also low.": "",
  "A patient with severe COPD is admitted with blood gas values showing pH 7.30, elevated pCO2, and elevated HCO3-. The physician notes the elevated bicarbonate indicates partial compensation. What primary acid-base disorder does this patient have?": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation": "",
  "Respiratory acidosis with renal (metabolic) compensation": "",
  "Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation": "",
  "Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation": "",
  "The COPD patient has chronic respiratory acidosis from CO2 retention due to impaired ventilation (elevated pCO2 lowers pH). The kidneys compensate over days by retaining bicarbonate (HCO3-) and excreting more H+, which is why bicarbonate is elevated, though the pH remains slightly low indicating partial compensation.": "",
  "A hospitalized patient with liver cirrhosis develops significant bilateral leg swelling and ascites (abdominal fluid accumulation). Laboratory results show a serum albumin of 1.8 g/dL (normal: 3.5-5.0). What mechanism best explains the edema?": "",
  "Increased aldosterone secretion causing sodium retention": "",
  "Decreased plasma oncotic pressure from low albumin, allowing fluid to shift from capillaries into the interstitial space": "",
  "Blocked lymphatic drainage in the legs": "",
  "Kidney failure causing inability to excrete water": "",
  "Albumin is the primary protein responsible for maintaining plasma oncotic (colloid osmotic) pressure, which normally keeps fluid within the capillaries. When albumin drops significantly due to liver failure, oncotic pressure decreases and fluid shifts out of the vascular space into the interstitial tissues, causing peripheral edema and ascites.": "",
  "A patient who has been vomiting repeatedly for three days is brought to the hospital. Blood work reveals pH 7.52, elevated HCO3-, and slightly elevated pCO2. What type of acid-base imbalance is present?": "",
  "Metabolic acidosis": "",
  "Respiratory acidosis": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis with partial respiratory compensation": "",
  "Respiratory alkalosis": "",
  "Prolonged vomiting causes loss of gastric hydrochloric acid (HCl), leading to metabolic alkalosis with elevated pH and bicarbonate. The body attempts to compensate by hypoventilating to retain CO2 (slightly elevated pCO2), but this compensation is limited by the need to maintain adequate oxygenation.": "",
  "An elderly nursing home patient is found obtunded. Lab work reveals serum sodium of 158 mEq/L and elevated serum osmolality. The staff reports the patient had limited access to water. What condition has developed, and what happened at the cellular level?": "",
  "Hypernatremia from water deficit, causing water to shift out of cells leading to cellular dehydration and neurological dysfunction": "",
  "Hypocalcemia causing muscle spasms and confusion": "",
  "Hyponatremia causing cells to swell with excess water": "",
  "Hyperkalemia causing cardiac arrhythmias": "",
  "This patient developed hypernatremia from inadequate water intake (water deficit). The elevated extracellular sodium creates a hypertonic environment that draws water out of cells by osmosis, causing cellular dehydration, particularly in brain cells, leading to altered mental status, lethargy, and potentially seizures or coma.": "",
  "A post-surgical patient on a diuretic develops muscle cramps, fatigue, and an ECG showing flattened T waves and U waves. The serum potassium level is 2.8 mEq/L. What electrolyte imbalance is present, and what is the most likely cause?": "",
  "Hyperkalemia caused by excessive potassium supplementation": "",
  "Hypocalcemia from inadequate calcium intake after surgery": "",
  "Hypokalemia caused by potassium loss from diuretic therapy": "",
  "Hypernatremia from excessive IV saline administration": "",
  "This patient has hypokalemia (K+ < 3.5 mEq/L), likely caused by the diuretic increasing potassium excretion in the urine. The characteristic ECG findings of flattened T waves and U waves, along with muscle cramps and fatigue, are classic manifestations of low potassium affecting cardiac and skeletal muscle function.": "",
  "A patient who recently had thyroid surgery develops tingling around her mouth and fingertips, followed by muscle spasms in her hands. The physician taps the facial nerve and observes twitching of the facial muscles (positive Chvostek's sign). What electrolyte imbalance is most likely responsible?": "",
  "Hyperkalemia from excessive potassium release during surgical tissue manipulation": "",
  "Hypomagnesemia from blood loss during surgery depleting circulating magnesium stores": "",
  "Hypocalcemia from accidental damage to the parathyroid glands during surgery": "",
  "Hyponatremia from intravenous fluid dilution of serum sodium during the procedure": "",
  "Post-thyroidectomy hypocalcemia occurs when the parathyroid glands are accidentally damaged or removed during surgery, causing a rapid drop in PTH and serum calcium. Low calcium increases neuromuscular excitability, producing tetany (muscle spasms), perioral tingling, and positive Chvostek's and Trousseau's signs.": "",
  "A trauma patient arrives at the ER in hemorrhagic shock after a car accident. The physician orders rapid infusion of lactated Ringer's solution. Why is an isotonic crystalloid chosen for initial fluid resuscitation rather than plain water?": "",
  "Plain water is too expensive for hospital use": "",
  "Lactated Ringer's contains antibiotics to prevent infection": "",
  "Plain water cannot be given intravenously under any circumstances": "",
  "Isotonic solutions remain primarily in the extracellular space to restore blood volume, whereas plain water would distribute into cells and cause hemolysis": "",
  "Isotonic crystalloid solutions like lactated Ringer's have the same osmolality as plasma, so the infused fluid remains primarily in the extracellular (vascular and interstitial) compartment, effectively restoring blood volume. Infusing pure water IV would be hypotonic, causing water to shift into cells by osmosis, which swells and lyses red blood cells (hemolysis) and fails to restore intravascular volume.": ""
}